<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="jn1006b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="jn1" href="#jn1006">JN1: </a>  <a href="../../ff/unbs/jn1all.htm#jn1006b"> (NLI.2A) 6(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> . . . There are three conditions of art: the lyrical, the epical and the dramatic. That art is lyrical whereby the artist sets forth the image in immediate relation to himself; that art is epical whereby the artist sets forth the image in mediate relation to himself and to others; that art is dramatic whereby the artist sets forth the image in immediate relation to others .... <p class="diip"> (JasAJoyce / 6 Mar 1903 / Paris)</p> </blockquote> <dd class="well"><mm class="note">Note: Copied onto Yale 1.1-1v. See <cite>James Joyce Archive</cite> (New York: Garland, 1978), vol. 7, p. 107.</mm> </dd></dl>
